@Scott_Fontana @Grabaka_Hitman @TheJivemaster I'll say it's definitely gotten a bit better recently. I think a lot of the current commentators are a little bit more receptive to social media and the few calling out mistakes have gotten through.

@Grabaka_Hitman @Scott_Fontana @TheJivemaster Btw just something I'll add in, if a judge ever did do everything you were asking for, then that'd be absolutely brilliant. I'm more responding why it would be completely understandable that they don't, rather than that they shouldn't. I'd love a series like that.

Even though that Texas judge had his absolutely abhorrent card a few months ago, I saw people posting his LinkedIn account and everything. I'd never talk to the fans ever in a role like that
Can't believe your man that killed the cat grew up to be the joker.

@Grabaka_Hitman @TheJivemaster @Scott_Fontana There is no positive end goal. There's like 5 people that would read it and think "Ahhh thats interesting I never considered that" and then 50,000 people saying you should quit judging forever. Why put yourself through that when it's not even in the job description?

@Grabaka_Hitman @TheJivemaster @Scott_Fontana Let's say a judge makes a good decision and wants to speak about it. A decision universally agreed upon by everyone knowledgeable about judging. That article is still getting absolutely shit on by fans regardless. They're still gonna be called the worst judge in the sport.

@Grabaka_Hitman @TheJivemaster @Scott_Fontana If people take an interest in actually learning how judging is implemented, reaching out, going to courses etc. then there would be less of a gap.

Right now, we're asking judges to speak to the media and fans, who's only interest is in crucifying them for any wrong decision.

@Grabaka_Hitman @TheJivemaster @Scott_Fontana It's the same in any profession. If tomorrow Marc Goddard came out and criticized Derek's scorecard it'd be on every single twitter page and news website that Marc thinks Derek is terrible at his job. They can talk to each other about it in private and achieve the same.
@andyste123 I read this like Rhys had to fight someone to secure his fiancée's hand in marriage 😂

@TheJivemaster @Grabaka_Hitman @Scott_Fontana In my experience, a lot of judges are interested in talking about judging. They just don't want to be quoted and put on a website, especially when it comes to contradicting one of their peer's scorecards.

@TheJivemaster @Grabaka_Hitman @Scott_Fontana But the communication will be "I thought this person landed more shots, and it turns out I was wrong". At which point 17,000 people will be in your comments telling your employer to fire you because how dare you get something wrong.

Just drop some judges an email.

@Grabaka_Hitman @Scott_Fontana @TheJivemaster These aren't celebrities though. If the fans are going to be assholes, it's not part of their job to have to take that burden on. It's completely a passion project for very little money. If coaches, promotions or peers want to talk about judging, they'll have to contact 1 on 1.

@TheJivemaster @Grabaka_Hitman @Scott_Fontana There's 3 judges because judges are going to see different things. They might hear some shots landing or see shots landing that the others didnt. The commission don't have to look into anything because this is a perfect example of the system working. The right person won.

@Grabaka_Hitman @Scott_Fontana @TheJivemaster Many are open to speak privately. A judge isn't going to have those discussions in the open forum when they get told to kill themselves and have a hashtag for them to be fired if they score a close round to someone else.

Daniel O’Sullivan 🇮🇪 Vs Cameron Clements 🇮🇪

Men's MW

Clements takes the fight down with a beautiful double leg early and finishes not long after with a rear naked choke. Very quick win and impressive performance to take the gold against a talented O'Sullivan.

#IrishMMA

Colin Meagher 🇮🇪 Vs Jordan Furey 🇮🇪

Men's WW

Jordan has a lot of power and landed some big shots at times, but Colin's wrestling allowed him to push the fight against the cage and control from the top position, landing decent GnP shots. Tough fight. Meagher gets gold

#IrishMMA

Solomon Simon 🇮🇪 Vs Andrew Barrett 🇮🇪

Men's LW

Lots of pressure from Barrett and Simon was backing away to try and find some space to work. Barrett didn't give him a chance to breath and kept the fight in the clinch. Feels like a bit of an upset but Barrett gets gold

#IrishMMA

#IrishMMA

Nadine Abbott Bissett 🇮🇪 Vs Lisa Houston 🇮🇪

Woman's SW

MMA debut and fighting Nadine? Tough break for Lisa. Lisa threatened with a solid armbar early which looked close. Nadine survived well, landed her patented GnP and got an armbar with 1sec to go. Gold again.

#IrishMMA

Brian Manning 🇮🇪 Vs Cameron Clements 🇮🇪

Men's MW

CC gets the right flag after I gave him the British one at IMMAF. All is right again. Brian looked great, defending tds and landing shots, but a low ankle pick tripped him and Clements easily for an RNC not long after.

#IrishMMA

Men's MW

Dan pressures forward but he did walk into a lot of the offence of Tristan. Tristan threatened with triangles off his back but Dan's ground and pound was brutal and that was enough for him to get the decision.

#IrishMMA

FINALLY finished watching @IMMAFed's #2021MMAWorlds.

I counted through my tweets timeline and I watched over 350 fights, with over 400 competitors from all over the world, in 12 days.

The competition was fantastic and I'd recommend it to any MMA fan interesting in the next gen.

Shamsutdin Makhmudov 🇷🇺 Vs Rassul Khatayev 🇰🇿

Men's SHW

Rasul was pushing grappling early but got exhausted in round 2. Shamsutdin took advantage and started putting it on him in the second round to get a TKO stoppage. Shamsutdin gets the gold at SHW!

#2021MMAWorlds
Scrolling through to count how many fights I saw and see De Sousa has Brazil and now Bahrain here. Bound to have made mistakes along the way haha

Robin Enontekio 🇸🇪 Vs Dzhamal Medzhidov 🇷🇺

Men's LHW

Robin couldn't keep himself on his feet and Medzhidov scored an early TD in every round. From there, the Russian was able to keep the fight in those spots, landing ground and pound and he takes the gold by dec

#2021MMAWorlds

Rasul Magomedov 🇧🇭 Vs Shamil Kuramagomedov 🇷🇺

Men's HW

The second Shamil was stopping Rasul's TDs in r1, you knew this could be an upset. It was a tame fight as Shamil didn't want to overcommit, and when he did in r3 he got taken down. Close, but Rasul takes it.

#2021MMAWorlds

Fergus Jenkins 🇳🇿 Vs Iusup Magomedov 🇷🇺

Men's MW

Haka for Fergus' walkout. A lot more wrestling from Fergus than I expected. A lot of the fight took place in the clinch, with both defending TDs well. By split decision, Fergus brings the gold to New Zealand.

#2021MMAWorlds

Ramazan Gitinov 🇧🇭 Vs Jovidon Mahmudov 🇹🇯

Men's WW

Gitinov doesn't give opponents an opportunity to breathe. Jovidon managed to defend TDs, but the second Gitinov is touching you, he'll turn the corner and secure it. Routine win for the champ to regain his title

#2021MMAWorlds

Olga Lagodnaya 🇷🇺 Vs Aizhan Abdykadyr 🇰🇿

Woman's LW

Olga controlled the grappling early, but slowed down in round 2 as Aizhan charged forward. She managed to turn it around in the final round, and at 41 years old, Olga wins the IMMAF gold. Amazing.

#2021MMAWorlds

Kurban Idrisov 🇧🇭 Vs Salamat Isbulaev 🇷🇺

Men's LW

Brutal top control and pressure from Idrisov, which has been his story for the entire competition so far. Isbulaev threatened with some gogoplata attempts, but Idrisov worn him down to win in the final.

@Aaron_LaFarge Taking someone down and putting them into a position is "control", so it's not like we don't count top positions at all. But the hierarchy goes

1. Effective striking/grappling
2. Effective aggression
3. Control

@Aaron_LaFarge So if someone gets to mount and lays there, they're not scoring. Whereas someone on bottom side control might be throwing up Liam McGeary reverse triangles. Positions aren't "effective", it's what's done in those positions that is "effective".

@Aaron_LaFarge Mount isn't more effect than say bottom side control. It's usually better because it means you've got much more offence available than the guy in bottom of side control, but you don't score what's available, only what you actually do.

@Aaron_LaFarge From what I've been told talking to judges and from the judging criteria, being on top might be a sign of control but it isn't inherently "effective grappling". If you're in top guard but your opponent is throwing up subs and elbowing your face in, top guard isn't "effective".

@Aaron_LaFarge Pretending that they're hitting each other at the same sort of "damage level".

@Aaron_LaFarge Scoring strikes in any fight is quite easy. "Who hit the other person harder and more?". The main thing in the MMA judging criteria is the hierarchy. For example, it's very rare that control is ever used in the final scoring in an MMA round per the criteria.

@Aaron_LaFarge I think in that case, it's the pay structure of MMA to blame. People don't fight harder if there's guaranteed pay or a win bonus, so why have show/win?

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 Yeah he wasn't as light on his toes so he couldn't put Dustin in a box. You sometimes get fighters, Khabib is maybe another, that have so few experiences of different situations in the cage that a standard fighter sees every fight. Conor can't just chill and wait like a usual guy

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 He was also one of the best in the game at pushing opponents back to the cage, which is where 90% of his best work was done. Similar to Nick and Nate that way. But he needed his footwork to make that happen. The Eddie fight might have made him think he does better in open waters.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 It was hard to replicate because he wanted to implement his own leg kicks. He got a reputation for being an extremely quick starter, but I think it was natural before. He started with a strong shot, but then got on his toes and worked with what the opponent gave him. Forces now.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 Conor's lost a lot of what served him well. He uses head movement above footwork. He's no longer an extremely dynamic kickboxer. Since Diaz, Conor is exactly as you describe, a pressure boxer. In his rise he was closer to Wonderboy than Holloway.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 Yeah from my view, Volk's style of countering is to engage as soon as you are. He wants to dip and shift under yours and then come over. Very few fighters capable of pulling it off in the modern game due to the athleticism required. It also stifles the opponent's offence well.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 I think he's as big of an outlier due to his success with the blocks. It's very very hard to break through his high block, whereas Dustin or Jan are a little bit more hittable through theirs. Yan's high guard is a fortress.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 Absolutely. Got me looking up these Petr Yan and Volkanovski highlight videos looking at things I never really thought about haha. Volkanovski is a bit more of a throwback than I thought with his dipping overhook style. Like a much better Frankie Edgar.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 Yeah Yan is an extreme outlier. Exceptional at what he does. Although he's very open to body shots and relies on his absolutely exceptional conditioning to eat them. I don't think many could use his style and remain as open to those.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 Yeah I'd never really say Conor has a "great defence". He trades a lot of defence to produce the offence he wants. I think people don't realize he took a fair few whacks from Mendes on the feet as well.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 I think Justin Gaethje's more "living on the edge" style was a good example of a static blocking defence not working. He tried a classic boxing "cover up, lean into shots from the waist" but they'd just be tagging him left and right.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 Yeah I think movement plays in big too. Volk enters and dips for his offence, and defensively he retreats with his hands high. Conor wants to maintain range, so he doesn't want to retreat out, and he doesn't dip and jump in for offence. If he was blocking, he'd be static.
@AndyHickeyMMA @phre @MrTudorLeonte @CaoiltedeBarra That's a counterfeit stella glass.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 Conor is a counter puncher. You can't really land a lot of counter shots from behind a traditional guard. He's attempts to bet on his reflexes and reactions in order to produce offence.

@SST1I7 @freshyuchiha @MartialMind1 That's mostly a "boxing for MMA" thing. Because of the small gloves and availability of different techniques, most MMA fighters rely on not being there Vs blocking. Most of the time fighters cover up is with their back to the cage, which we've rarely seen with Conor.

@MartialMind1 I don't see boxing as a sport of "hitting and not getting hit". There's no points for not getting hit. It's "hitting the most / hardest". Some boxers opt to get in a dog fight and bet on themselves being the last one standing and if they are, they win the boxing match.

@MartialMind1 I had this conversation the other day, but there's many ways to box. The traditional Mexican style involves two guys standing on each other's toes and trading shots. Muhammad Ali liked to lay on the ropes and let opponents tire themselves out. There's different styles of boxing.
